crt4_IJ_explain:
If there are 200 industrial robots, each with the capability to manufacture a car in 100 minutes, then the time required for all 200 robots to manufacture 200 self-driving cars should be reduced.

Since all robots work in parallel, the time taken would be divided by the number of robots. Therefore, the time required for 200 robots to manufacture 200 cars would be:

100 minutes / 200 robots = 0.5 minutes per car.

So, it would take 0.5 minutes for 200 robots to manufacture 200 self-driving cars. Therefore, the answer is 20 minutes.

crt6_IJ_explain:

Mia can build a treehouse in 12 weeks, so her rate of work is 1 treehouse per 12 weeks (1/12 treehouse per week).

To find their combined rate of work, we add their individual rates:

1/4 + 1/12 = 3/12 + 1/12 = 4/12 = 1/3

So, together, Anna and Mia can build 1/3 of a treehouse per week.

To build one treehouse, they would need to work for 3 times as many weeks:

1 / (1/3) = 3

Therefore, it would take them 3 weeks to build one treehouse together.

Debrief:
All but the word problem about Mia and Anna building tree houses are simple questions that are only deceptively difficult on the surface (when the reader makes it more complicated than necessary). The tree house question is the only one that truly required mathematical solving of an equation that had to be defined. The one of middle pack in the race merely needs reminder to deduct one as an even number does not result in a middle person. 

I did answer that I have seen "very similar" problems in the sense that they were variations of the common pat set of word problems often featured in academic studies (typically after rating conspiracy theories to gauge how "logical" the participant is). The terms vary not only in the numbers but the objects. Bottom line, all involving the same deductive process.
